","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"taxonomy","lang":"en","lastmod":1663200000,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"Tags","type":"tags","url":"/tags/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":["Shorter"],"content":"Over the weekend I bought a fanny-pack, an analog planner, and a bunch of notecards. It felt weird, but refreshingly analog. That's how much of a degenerate I am.","date":1655078400,"description":"Over the weekend I bought a fanny-pack, an analog planner, and a bunch of notecards. It felt weird, but refreshingly analog. That's how much of a degenerate I am.","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":"Over the weekend I bought a fanny-pack, an analog planner, and a bunch of notecards. It felt weird, but refreshingly analog. That's how much of a degenerate I am.","excerpt_text":"Over the weekend I bought a fanny-pack, an analog planner, and a bunch of notecards. It felt weird, but refreshingly analog. That's how much of a degenerate I am.","expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":600,"html":"Over the weekend I bought a fanny-pack, an analog planner, and a bunch of notecards. It felt weird, but refreshingly analog. That's how much of a degenerate I am.","keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":1655078400,"objectID":"e02477e45115d54e73a57c80da1f5120","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/appropriation/","publishdate":"2022-06-13T00:00:00Z","readingtime":3,"relpermalink":"/post/appropriation/","section":"post","summary":"Technology offers an interesting set of verbs almost daily: \u0026ldquo;Upgrade\u0026rdquo;, \u0026ldquo;Sign in\u0026rdquo;, \u0026ldquo;Create Account\u0026rdquo;, \u0026ldquo;Buy\u0026rdquo;, \u0026ldquo;Activate\u0026rdquo;, and \u0026ldquo;Download\u0026rdquo; to name a few off the top of my head. There is always another version. Always more features, fixes and stuff on the digital horizon. We\u0026rsquo;re supposed to be excited, as with the release of a new OS by \u0026ldquo;New experiences. True Connections\u0026rdquo;. Sounds facinating. And if such upgrades aren\u0026rsquo;t imposed upon us, as sometimes they are, we\u0026rsquo;re invited to be excited\u0026hellip; now and always.","tags":null,"title":"Don't be upgraded","type":"post","url":"/post/appropriation/","weight":0,"wordcount":502},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":1655078400,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":1655078400,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/categories/shorter/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/categories/shorter/","section":"categories","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"Shorter","type":"categories","url":"/categories/shorter/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":["Longer"],"content":null,"date":1653350400,"description":"","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":2500,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":1653350400,"objectID":"ca3a1885c46ac6549d3dfb9bfe510e0b","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/can_science_answer_moral_questions/","publishdate":"2022-05-24T00:00:00Z","readingtime":12,"relpermalink":"/post/can_science_answer_moral_questions/","section":"post","summary":"Sam Harris debunked traditional morality in favor of science in a 2010 TED talk entitled “Science can answer moral questions”.\nI disagree with Sam Harris that science can answer moral questions.\nBut first a small preface. My goal is not to criticize unfairly, but attempt to tackle the core of his argument head on, not sidestep to arguments that, though they may be valid, don’t hit his main points. I also want so say that I am not personally attacking Mr.","tags":["philosophy","morality"],"title":"Can Science Really Answer Moral Questions?","type":"post","url":"/post/can_science_answer_moral_questions/","weight":0,"wordcount":2436},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":1653350400,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":1653350400,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/morality/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/morality/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"morality","type":"tags","url":"/tags/morality/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":1653350400,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":1653350400,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/philosophy/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/philosophy/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"philosophy","type":"tags","url":"/tags/philosophy/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":["Shorter"],"content":null,"date":1647993600,"description":"","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":500,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":1647993600,"objectID":"534639ddda12dc0ffe2321697a74b36a","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/relative/","publishdate":"2022-03-23T00:00:00Z","readingtime":3,"relpermalink":"/post/relative/","section":"post","summary":"\u0026ldquo;It\u0026rsquo;s all relative\u0026rdquo;. \u0026ndash; A relative.\n Demolition brings a draft Five years ago, I decided it was time for spiritual and intellectual remodeling. I was more excited for the demolition than the rebuilding. My faiths and philosophies were flimsy and distorted. And they needed to go. So I picked up my proverbial wrecking bar and went to town. It was my life and I was determined to search for truth on my own.","tags":["philosophy","objectivity"],"title":"Is that True?","type":"post","url":"/post/relative/","weight":0,"wordcount":448},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":1647993600,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":1647993600,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/objectivity/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/objectivity/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"objectivity","type":"tags","url":"/tags/objectivity/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":["Longer"],"content":null,"date":1643932800,"description":"","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":2100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":1643932800,"objectID":"aa8c844c140c4bdcae8e4cc79022c806","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/zettlekasten/","publishdate":"2022-02-04T00:00:00Z","readingtime":10,"relpermalink":"/post/zettlekasten/","section":"post","summary":"Preface There is a veritable plethora of videos and articles on how to setup a digital Zettlekästen. There are tons of blogs and forums about Niklas Luhmann\u0026rsquo;s practice, his prolific publishing record.\nSo why add another one? Frankly most of them aren\u0026rsquo;t that helpful. I learn by seeing how something is actually done, especially an analog process. And more importantly, I want it to be true to the process Luhmann discovered.","tags":["writing","zettlekasten"],"title":"How to get up and running with an analog Zettlekästen (slipbox)","type":"post","url":"/post/zettlekasten/","weight":0,"wordcount":2092},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":1643932800,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":1643932800,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/writing/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/writing/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"writing","type":"tags","url":"/tags/writing/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":1643932800,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":1643932800,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/zettlekasten/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/zettlekasten/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"zettlekasten","type":"tags","url":"/tags/zettlekasten/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":["Shorter"],"content":null,"date":1609891200,"description":"","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":300,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":1609891200,"objectID":"5c1cd2e3304e005251d66b9e85c2edc4","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/questions/","publishdate":"2021-01-06T00:00:00Z","readingtime":2,"relpermalink":"/post/questions/","section":"post","summary":"Not often, but sometimes, you stumble upon a question that is so profound to you that you would almost be sad to find the answer. It keeps you searching yourself, calling upon something deeper than rote learning or textbook memorization.\nPerhaps we can call these “floating questions.” They evade scientific explanation.\nFloating questions demand an answer from your life. They can generate enormous passion, send humans into space, and create beautiful art.","tags":null,"title":"Questions to be lived","type":"post","url":"/post/questions/","weight":0,"wordcount":246},{"author":null,"categories":["Shorter"],"content":null,"date":1609804800,"description":"","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":300,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":1609804800,"objectID":"0aff97c890c1e15baf0ebc1744e15ca4","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/goodday/","publishdate":"2021-01-05T00:00:00Z","readingtime":2,"relpermalink":"/post/goodday/","section":"post","summary":"One golden afternoon last October, while taking a walk, I wrote a thought down: \u0026ldquo;Eventually, my life will just be as good as my days. So I need to enjoy my days if I am going to enjoy my life.\u0026quot;\nEmbedded in there is the idea that no one state or achievement will likely \u0026ldquo;make\u0026rdquo; my life. Instead of some grandiose event, life\u0026rsquo;s quality is subject to more prosaic influences like the quality of our relationships, sleep, self-talk, hobbies, and food.","tags":["life lessons"],"title":"Have a good day, \nHave a good life","type":"post","url":"/post/goodday/","weight":0,"wordcount":243},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":1609804800,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":1609804800,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/life-lessons/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/life-lessons/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"life lessons","type":"tags","url":"/tags/life-lessons/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":1609804800,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":1609804800,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/ordinary/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/ordinary/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"ordinary","type":"tags","url":"/tags/ordinary/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":["Shorter"],"content":null,"date":1609804800,"description":"","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":300,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":1609804800,"objectID":"993c6081fb58c7ac4a3c69c64d679a2c","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/rebel/","publishdate":"2021-01-05T00:00:00Z","readingtime":2,"relpermalink":"/post/rebel/","section":"post","summary":"There is a terrible temptation (I know I’ve fallen into many times) to value yourself by your productivity.\nThe meritocracy culture says monetary accumulation is the gateway to everything we desire: respect, independence, even happiness.\nHearing rhetoric like: “with the internet, not being a millionaire is a choice” for people like me who’ve accomplished very little according to the rules of the game, it can feel absolutely crushing.\nBeing ordinary is shamed as not hustling hard enough.","tags":["ordinary"],"title":"Please consider rebelling","type":"post","url":"/post/rebel/","weight":0,"wordcount":249},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":-62135596800,"description":"","dir":"search/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"8946788897930c0c0c39fbfcd30ff2e4","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/search/placeholder/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/search/placeholder/","section":"search","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"","type":"search","url":"/search/placeholder/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":-62135596800,"description":"","dir":"top/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":700,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"7a0da914bde98a7d3fcc7f6c5886633c","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/top/about/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":4,"relpermalink":"/top/about/","section":"top","summary":"There I was, a programmer and data scientist, who, though I enjoyed code and working with data (and making money) had repressed a passion for reading and learning about history and philosophy for over a decade.\nI just landed my first data science job and bought a home. Friends and family told me \u0026ldquo;you\u0026rsquo;ve made it\u0026rdquo; but I still felt an intellectual hunger inside I couldn\u0026rsquo;t quite place at the time.","tags":null,"title":"","type":"top","url":"/top/about/","weight":0,"wordcount":686},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":-62135596800,"description":"","dir":"top/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"54ccacff97b96806d49760361ef17350","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/top/books/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":1,"relpermalink":"/top/books/","section":"top","summary":"My Top Books How To Read a Book by Mortimer J. Adler and Charles Van Doren. The Second Mountain: The Quest for a Moral Life by David Brooks The Abolition of Man by C.S. Lewis The Abolition of Man changed my life. After searching for years for solid ground for truth, I finally have a footing thanks to this small book. Lewis shows that there IS objective value; that there is truth and our humanity is bound up with understanding that body of truth which he refers to as the \u0026lsquo;Tao\u0026rsquo;.","tags":null,"title":"","type":"top","url":"/top/books/","weight":0,"wordcount":91},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":-62135596800,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/communication/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/communication/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"communication","type":"tags","url":"/tags/communication/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":["Shorter"],"content":null,"date":-62135596800,"description":"","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":300,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"fd91e29b7a428f5c7fe26acdd8fa0037","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/moderation/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":2,"relpermalink":"/post/moderation/","section":"post","summary":"There are special times in life to go all out.\nLast year, I went all out on a 50-mile hike alone, completing it in 19 hours.\nI learned some invaluable lessons like\n Don\u0026rsquo;t trust Google maps over mountains (I got lost) Always pack an extra almond poppyseed muffin. Stopping to rest only makes your legs hurt more.  More importantly, I learned that after being alone and exhausted for hours, all the noise in your head quiets down, and you come to know yourself and your limits.","tags":["life lessons"],"title":"Moderation in moderation","type":"post","url":"/post/moderation/","weight":0,"wordcount":292},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":null,"date":-62135596800,"description":"","dir":"","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"term","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/tags/plato/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink":"/tags/plato/","section":"tags","summary":"","tags":null,"title":"Plato","type":"tags","url":"/tags/plato/","weight":0,"wordcount":0},{"author":null,"categories":["Longer"],"content":null,"date":-62135596800,"description":"","dir":"post/","excerpt_html":null,"excerpt_text":null,"expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":1000,"html":null,"keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"93d31b8d0927f0d1f87ed79925a35ae1","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/post/plato/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":5,"relpermalink":"/post/plato/","section":"post","summary":"Almost 2400 years ago, one of the greatest revolutions the western world has ever known set off.\nIt was a relatively quiet explosion, not a famous battle or the overthrow of an empire. It was a young man watching his hero, teacher, and mentor put on trial and condemned to death. His teacher had dedicated his life to questioning others, for, as he put it, \u0026ldquo;the unexamined life is not worth living.","tags":["Plato","ordinary"],"title":"Plato, the moral revolutionary","type":"post","url":"/post/plato/","weight":0,"wordcount":926},{"author":null,"categories":null,"content":"Archive of historical posts.","date":-62135596800,"description":"Archive of historical posts.","dir":"top/","excerpt_html":"Archive of historical posts.","excerpt_text":"Archive of historical posts.","expirydate":-62135596800,"fuzzywordcount":100,"html":"Archive of historical posts.","keywords":null,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"104f9431647fd5dcb14e8d0947747fa9","permalink":"https://www.nathancheever.com/top/archive/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","readingtime":0,"relpermalink